By Marie Cook 

Some events require different facilities for convenience. In sports, for instance, there are cases when you have to provide seats for the spectators to comfortably watch the game. It, therefore, makes it necessary for you to acquire them from a particular leasing company or individual. You are likely to find many bleachers for rent IN , but this does not make all of them the best for your case. For that reason, consider the following factors before you make a choice.

The first and one of the most important considerations is the leasing fee. Remember that the companies that are offering these facilities are in business. Therefore, they are out to make money, even as they offer you the assistance you need. Avoid charges that are likely to cripple your other activities. The facility you decide to take is supposed to be standard and affordable to you.

The second element pertains the distance to be covered. Consider keenly the amount of time you are likely to spend at your chosen venue and the location of your facility. This distance affects the time of transportation, thereby affecting the general schedule of activities. It is advisable to go for facilities that are located near you and which can be easily accessed.

Element number three touches on the general company integrity. Business is a very fragile venture, and one is supposed to be very keen with the individuals they choose to do business with. If you engage a company whose public image is deformed, the effects can be very disastrous to you. Spend enough time asking about the particular company you want to engage in the provision of the facilities.

The degree of your satisfaction as the client and that of your spectators will largely depend on the level of services you will be offered. Some companies always ensure that their clients get the best kinds of services, including bonuses. For others, the service ends once they deliver the seats. Therefore, make your decision based on informed opinions.

The type of event for which you are acquiring the facilities is another factor you must keep in mind. Some field events do not attract many spectators while others do attract a huge audience. Having a clear understanding of this will help you to budget concisely and make the right decisions. Otherwise, you run the risk of acquiring insufficient facilities or too many beyond what is necessary.

If you have any experience in the same area, use it to your advantage. Previous experiences are important in offering lessons that one can use to make better decisions. Some experiences can be helpful in enhancing the quality of services that one gets while others can help in cutting down the costs.

Considering the aforementioned factors, you need a keener eye to make the right choice. One is advised to have a checklist of items to look at before setting out. You will realize that this method helped you to make the right decisions.

import scala.language.experimental.macros

import scala.reflect.macros.blackbox

object F {
  def f[T](t: T): Option[T] = macro impl[T]
  def impl[T: c.WeakTypeTag](c: blackbox.Context)(
      t: c.Expr[T]): c.Expr[Option[T]] = {
    import c.universe._
    val bound = collection.mutable.Buffer.empty[(c.Tree, ValDef)]
    val OptionGet = typeOf[Option[_]].member(TermName("get"))
    val transformed = c.internal.typingTransform(t.tree) {
      case (t @ q"$fun.$get", api) if t.symbol == OptionGet =>
        val tempName = c.freshName(TermName("tmp"))
        // use api.currentOwner instead of c.internal.enclosingOwner
        val tempSym = c.internal.newTermSymbol(api.currentOwner, tempName)
        c.internal.setInfo(tempSym, t.tpe)
        val tempIdent = Ident(tempSym)
        c.internal.setType(tempIdent, t.tpe)
        bound.append((fun, c.internal.valDef(tempSym)))
        tempIdent
      case (t, api) => api.default(t)
    }
    val embedded = q"${bound(0)._1}.map(${bound(0)._2} => $transformed )"
    println(embedded)
    c.Expr[Option[T]](embedded)
  }
}

ျမန္မာ့ပင္လယ္ျပင္ တြင္ မြန္-တနသၤာရီကမ္း႐ိုးတန္းတေလၽွာက္ႏွင့္ ကမ္းလြန္ ပင္လယ္ျပင္တို႔တြင္ တစ္ခါတစ္ရံ အေရွ႕ဘက္မွ ေလျပင္းမ်ားတိုက္ခတ္ၿပီး၊ လႈိင္းအသင့္အတင့္မွ လႈိင္းႀကီးႏိုင္ေၾကာင္း၊ အေရွ႕ဘက္မွ ေလျပင္းမ်ား တိုက္ခတ္စဥ္ ေရျပင္/ေျမျပင္ေလသည္ တစ္နာရီလၽွင္ မိုင္(၃၀)မွ (၃၅)မိုင္ အထိ တိုက္ခတ္ႏိုင္ေၾကာင္း၊ က်န္ျမန္မာ့ ပင္လယ္ျပင္တြင္ လႈိင္းအနည္း ငယ္မွ အသင့္အတင့္ရွိမည္ျဖစ္ေၾကာင္း၊ လႈိင္းအျမင့္မွာ မြန္-တနသၤာရီ ကမ္း႐ိုးတန္း တေလၽွာက္ႏွင့္ ကမ္းလြန္ပင္လယ္ျပင္တို႔တြင္ (၆)ေပမွ (၉)ေပခန္႔ႏွင့္ က်န္ျမန္မာ့ပင္လယ္ျပင္တြင္ (၃)ေပမွ (၅)ေပခန္႔ ရွိႏိုင္ေၾကာင္း သတင္းထုတ္ျပန္ခ်က္ထဲတြင္ ပါရွိသည္။ (Xinhua)

04:13 AM EST Global B2B Marketplace, iiSnap Helping Manufacturers Sell Internationally with First to Market Buying Model 
iiSnap, the Western Australia based start-up company is disrupting the traditional distribution model, enabling manufacturing companies to sell directly to retailers and gain significant savings by removing barriers to entry. iiSnap has introduced a first to market buying model that forecast demand and group retailers orders to meet suppliers MOQ (minimum order quantity) goal. 
“As Retail becomes more and more challenging for businesses; we want to give retailers the opportunity to have a new edge over the big competitors by providing them access to higher margins and exciting products" stated Ami Barda, founder of iiSnap. 
"We also want to empower smaller businesses because 80% of the buying force in the market of consumer products purchasing is small to medium enterprises." 
iiSnap has partnered with some of the leading companies in the supply chain industry to offer end to end buying and selling solutions that includes secure payment processing, quality control, fulfillments, and shipping. 
Products will be available across a wide range of categories including lifestyle tech, kids & family, Outdoors tech, wearables, fitness and leisure as well as audio and entertainment. 
iiSnap mainly focuses on tech and design-centric brands with unique product offering, companies currently on-boarding the site will be able to sell directly to specialty retailers in their industry with the aim to have a passionate and motivated retailer behind the sale process. 
The company has managed to automate the complicated procurement process to provide SME's buyers with a transparent and seamless buying experience that saves them time and money. 
iiSnap offers low barriers to entry for vendors with no subscription or membership fees but simply straightforward marketplace fees on orders placed on the platform. 
“The aim was always to develop a win-win scenario; No sales? No Fees. Our aim is to bring the margins back to the retailers, the innovative products to the consumers, and the profits back to the manufacturers” says Barda. 
iiSnap is open to new suppliers applications and buyers interested can request an invitation on the company home page

posts.text:
Published: 12:35 am   From left, trainer Joseph O’Brien, owner Lloyd Williams, and jockey Corey Brown pose with their winning trophies after Rekindling wins the Melbourne Cup at Flemington Racecourse in Melbourne, Australia, Tuesday, Nov. 7, 2017. (AP Photo/Andy Brownbill) 
MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) — Rekindling stormed home to win the Melbourne Cup by a long neck on Tuesday, overhauling Johannes Vermeer near the finish to give trainer Joseph O’Brien a victory over his famous father in Australia’s most famous race. 
Max Dynamite was 2 ½ lengths further back in third to give the Irish a 1-2-3 finish in the 157th running of the 2-mile classic. 
Joseph O’Brien said one of the first things he did was phone his father, Aidan O’Brien, who trains Johannes Vermeer but was not at Flemington for the race. 
“He is delighted. Unbelievable,” the younger O’Brien said. “I’m just so thankful to (Williams). They suggested to bring (Rekindling) down and that he’d have a good chance in the race and his prep went really good, and Corey gave him an unbelievable ride.” 
It was a second Melbourne Cup victory for jockey Corey Brown, and a sixth for owner Lloyd Williams, who is also a co-owner of Johannes Vermeer. 
“It’s extraordinary, absolutely extraordinary,” Williams said of Joseph O’Brien, who won in his first attempt at the Melbourne Cup. Williams said the 24-year-old former jockey had a big future as a trainer. “He’s going to emulate his father and maybe more.” 
Big Duke was the first Australian-trained horse across the line, finishing fourth, in a field containing 11 foreign horses. 
British-based jockey Frankie Dettori rode 2016 winner Almandin, which finished 12th.

posts.text: Larger text size Very large text size Single Gaze pulled up lame, has a black eye and got smashed in her first Melbourne Cup, but jockey Kathy O'Hara backs the gutsy mare to bounce back with a potential return to the $6.2 million race next year. Canberra trainer Nick Olive's only concern was for the welfare of his horse - although he admits he's hungry to return to the Cup after getting a taste for it this spring carnival. Kathy O'Hara says Single Gaze could return to the Melbourne Cup next year. Photo: Tracey Neamy Single Gaze finished 17th, almost 16 lengths behind winner Rekindling, but Olive said she should have finished "100 metres last" with the run she had. The Canberra mare was checked several times throughout the race, including the opening 200m when Italian jockey Frankie Dettori squeezed in on her . Dettori escaped sanction from Racing Victoria stewards over the incident. Advertisement It effectively ended O'Hara's hopes in her first Melbourne Cup, where she became just the sixth female jockey to ride in the great race. O'Hara said the whole Cup experience had been "awesome" and she was hopeful of a return to the big stage again in the future - potentially on Single Gaze. They combined to finish second in the Caulfield Cup, which launched her on a path to the race that stops a nation. She felt an autumn campaign including the $4 million group 1 Queen Elizabeth Stakes at Randwick could also be on the cards. "It's been awesome, it's just disappointing that things went that way, but that's racing," O'Hara said. "She's going to be in for a good autumn I would imagine and contest all the top races there and she's already shown that she's well up to it and she might have another crack [at the Cup] next year. "She was brave, even though she was knocked around from pillar to post, she still made a bit of a run at them and she was going past some tired horses there at the finish." A potential trip to Hong Kong was on the cards for December , but changes to quarantine laws mean she won't make the trip. Olive said she would go to the paddock for a well-earned rest and he was hopeful there was nothing wrong with her. He said he would make a decision on where to race next once she'd been assessed and had some time to recover. "She got battered around a bit, she'll be pretty sore and sorry tomorrow I'd say. She'll be well and truly looking for the paddock ... she's got a black eye as well," Olive said. "I'll just let everything settle before I make a decision on that. Just a good spell, a good break." Olive was "super proud" of Single Gaze and said she'd gone to another level this campaign, where her second in the Caulfield Cup meant she became the first Canberra horse to accrue $2 million in prizemoney. He said the lead up to the Melbourne Cup had been "one of the greatest weeks of his life" and he was desperate to get there again. Single Gaze could be the horse to get him there, with Olive convinced her run proved she could handle the distance. "I'm just really proud of her, she's absolutely been smashed up. She's only little and that's the disadvantage in a pressure race like the Melbourne Cup when you've got to try and hold your ground against bigger and stronger horses," Olive said. posts.text:
Brandconnect 7 Hal yang Harus Diperhatikan Wanita Karier dalam Mengelola Keuangan Kepala Divisi Komunikasi BPJS Ketenagakerjaan, Irvansyah Utoh Banja menjelaskan bahwa Turnamen BFC 2017 yang mengangkat tema "Ciptakan Harmoni di Lapangan Untuk Juara Teladan" ini sejalan dengan semangat 40 Tahun BPJS Ketenagakerjaan yang telah melindungi seluruh pekerja di Indonesia. "Turnamen ini merupakan agenda tahunan yang diselenggarakan menjelang perayaan HUT BPJS Ketenagakerjaan, di mana setiap tim dan peserta wajib terdaftar sebagai peserta BPJS Ketenagakerjaan. Ini juga merupakan bentuk apresiasi kami terhadap para peserta yang selama ini telah terlindungi oleh program jaminan sosial ketenagakerjaan dari BPJS Ketenagakerjaan," kata Utoh di Jakarta, Minggu (5/11/2017) lalu. 
Baca: Test Event Asian Games, Cabor Menembak Uji Coba Nomor Baru Utoh menambahkan, Turnamen BFC ini juga selalu dijadikan sebagai ajang pemanasan sebelum tim-tim peserta tampil di turnamen bergengsi lainnya. "Mayoritas tim dari kalangan BUMN selalu menjadikan ajang BFC sebagai ajang pemanasan sebelum mereka tampil di Porseni BUMN. Demikian halnya dengan tim dari kalangan korporasi swasta, instansi pemerintah maupun media yang menjadikan ajang BFC sebagai agenda rutin untuk mengukur prestasi tim mereka," Utoh menandaskan. Ketua Panitia BFC 2017, Mohamad Ridwan mengungkapkan, turnamen kali ini merupakan penyelenggaraan yang kedepalan secara beruntun sejak pertama kali dihelat pada 2009 silam. Menurut Ridwan, dalam setiap penyelenggaraan Turnamen BFC ini selalu menampilkan juara-juara baru, dimana pada penyelenggaraan BFC 2016 lalu tim futsal Bank BNI keluar sebagai Juara satu. Sedangkan gelar runner up direbut oleh Bank BRI, Juara tiga Bank BNI Syariah dan Juara empat PT Surya Toto. Sesuai dengan angka ulang tahun BPJS Ketenagakerjaan yang ke-40 tahun, pada penyelenggaraan turnamen BFC 2017 ini, lanjut Ridwan, jumlah peserta juga disesuaikan menjadi 40 tim. Di mana 16 tim harus terlebih dahulu melewati babak kualifikasi sebelum tampil di babak 32 besar untuk berhadapan dengan 24 tim yang langsung mendapatkan wild card berdasarkan undian. Turnamen di bagi dua hari dimana pada hari pertama akan dilangsungkan babak kualifikasi hingga ke babak 16 besar. Sementara hari kedua pertandingan babak 16 besar dilanjutkan hingga babak grand final. Sebelum partai grand final akan dimainkan pertandingan eksebisi yang mempertemukan tim yang diperkuat Menteri Ketenagakerjaan RI, M Hanif Dhakiri dan Direktur Utama BPJS Ketenagakerjaan, Agus Susanto melawan tim wartawan yang sehari-hari meliput sektor ketenagakerjaan. Selain Turnamen BFC, agenda besar perayaan HUT ke-40 BPJS Ketenagakerjaan juga akan dimeriahkan dengan rangkaian kegiatan yang bertema "40 Jam Bersama BPJS Ketenagakerjaan" di Indonesia Convention Exhibition (ICE), BSD City Tangerang, Banten yang akan digelar selama 40 jam nonstop tanggal 15-17 Desember 2017 mendatang. Rangkaian kegiatan tersebut diantaranya diisi dengan berbagai kompetisi seperti basket 3 on 3. Acara besar ini nantinya akan dimeriahkan oleh sejumlah artis papan atas seperti Slank dan Via Vallent, juga akan digelar lomba ketahanan fisik "Touch The House", dimana peserta terakhir yang bertahan ditetapkan sebagai pemenang dan mendapatkan hadiah utama sebuah rumah. Khusus untuk kalangan jurnalis, BPJS Ketenagakerjaan juga kembali menggelar lomba karya tulis jurnalistik bertajuk "BPJS Ketenagakerjaan Journalistic Award 2017". posts.title: Cómo hacer un disfraz en 5 minutos
posts.text:
Halloween es una de esas fechas que para mí pasaba de largo. Nunca me había disfrazado en Halloween y no tenía intención de hacerlo, bastante tenía con carnavales. Pero nació Maia y las fiestas de Halloween para peques llegaron a mi vida. 

El año pasado estando Maia en la guardería ya nos dijeron que iban a celebrar Halloween y que la lleváramos disfrazada, como soy así, pasé del tema y al final la disfrazaron allí con lo típico, un gorro en la cabeza y cosas por estilo. 
Maia súper contenta con su gorro xD 
Pero este año no me he podido escapar y aun así lo dejé todo para el último momento.

Este año Halloween caía en martes y el viernes antes al ir a recoger a la enana al colegio unas madres me dijeron que el bar Etxebarri hacía fiesta de Halloween para los peques con barra libre de comida y bebida para los que fueran disfrazados. 

Viernes 17:30 y yo sin disfraz para Maia, pero Dondisfraz.com me salvó la vida. Hice el pedido y el sábado por la mañana tenía mi disfraz para la enana por 15€.
Maia con su disfraz de esqueleto 
Pensaba que ya podía relajarme, tenía el disfraz de Maia, no necesitaba más, ¡pero no!
El mismo martes al ir a recoger a la peque las madres me dijeron que ellas también se iban a disfrazar y que para los adultos también había cosas si íbamos disfrazados. 
¡Caos! Eran las 16:30 y la fiesta empezaba a las 17:30.

Me vestí toda de negro, me puse la cara blanca con polvos de talco de la enana (olía a bebé que no veas), me puse los ojos un poco negros, me envolví todo el cuerpo con papel higiénico y lo pegué con celo para no perder el papel, manché un poco la ropa con sangre liquida que tenía por casa (puede ser tomate) y ¡listo! Era una momia low cost.

By JOE McDONALD
BEIJING (AP) — Global stocks rose Tuesday after Wall Street posted modest gains on deal reports and oil prices rose for a second day following turmoil in Saudi Arabia.
KEEPING SCORE: In early trading, France's CAC 40 rose 0.3 percent to 5,523.22 and London's FTSE 100 advanced 0.1 percent to 7,571.24. Germany's DAX was little changed at 13,468.79. On Monday, the CAC 40 lost 0.2 percent and the DAX retreated 0.1 percent while the FTSE 100 eked out a small gain. On Wall Street, the future for the Dow Jones industrial average rose 0.2 percent while that for the Standard & Poor's 500 index gained 0.1 percent. The previous session, the S&P gained 0.1 percent, the Dow added less than 0.1 percent and the Nasdaq composite gained 0.3 percent.
ASIA'S DAY: Tokyo's Nikkei 225 jumped 1.7 percent to 22,937.60 and the Shanghai Composite Index rose 0.7 percent to 3,413.57. Hong Kong's Hang Seng advanced 1.3 percent to 28,983.62 and Sydney's S&P-ASX 200 added 1 percent to 6,014.30. Seoul's Kospi lost 0.2 percent to 2,545.44 and India's Sensex shed 0.6 percent to 33,536.89. Benchmarks in Taiwan, Singapore and Jakarta rose while New Zealand and Manila declined.
WALL STREET: Chipmakers surged after Broadcom offered to buy competitor Qualcomm for $103 billion, which if completed would be the largest tech acquisition ever. Reports that Sprint's owner, Japanese conglomerate SoftBank, might buy cable company Charter hammered shares of telecom giants AT&T and Verizon, which might face tougher competition. Sellers of household goods slumped on weak quarterly results from CVS Health and food distributor Sysco. Twenty-First Century Fox and Disney both climbed after a report Disney might buy Fox assets.
SAUDI TURMOIL: A wave of arrests of princes and other officials in what the Saudi leadership says is an anti-corruption crackdown sent shockwaves through global oil markets, pushing prices to two-year highs. Saudi Arabia is the world's largest exporter of oil. Energy companies jumped and drilling companies made some of the biggest gains. Skeptics of the sweep say it targets potential rivals or possible critics of Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, who heads the anti-corruption committee that was formed Saturday shortly before the arrests.
ANALYST'S TAKE: "The Saudi corruption purge is boosting crude oil prices. But while this may sound like bad news from an economic perspective, it may actually be good news for Asia," said Rob Carnell of IG in a report. "The current rise means the Middle East will hopefully be buying more of what is made in this part of the world, and provide a boost to what is otherwise a rather narrow semiconductor-driven export rise."
TRUMP WATCH: U.S. President Donald Trump, in Seoul in the midst of a 12-day Asian tour, said efforts to curb North Korea's nuclear weapons program would be "front and center" in his visit. He projected optimism that rising tensions could be abated peacefully. South Korean police mobilized 15,000 officers for rallies due to be held by Trump's critics and supporters. Many South Koreans are concerned that Trump's fiery rhetoric on North Korea is raising the threat of war.
ENERGY: Benchmark U.S. crude gained 1 cent to $57.36 per barrel in electronic trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The contract surged $1.70 on Monday to close at $57.35. Brent crude, used to price international oils, rose 12 cents to $64.21 in London. It soared $2.20 the previous session to $64.27.
CURRENCY: The dollar climbed to 114.14 yen from Monday's 113.71. The euro declined to $1.1593 from $1.1612.
